<h1 class="hero-h">Which workflows <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">should AI touch first?</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The most common failure mode in AI rollouts is doing too many things at once. This framework gives you a way to score and rank the 10-30 candidate workflows that emerge from any honest audit — so you can confidently pick the 3 that ship first.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The scoring model</span><h2 class="h2">Five dimensions, 1-5 each</h2><p class="body">Score each candidate workflow on five dimensions. Total score is out of 25. Use the top 3 for your first wave. Everything else goes on a ranked backlog.</p><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>What 5/5 looks like</th><th>What 1/5 looks like</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Time leverage</strong></td><td>Saves 8+ hours/week per user; multiple users</td><td>Saves under 30 minutes/week; one user</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AI fit</strong></td><td>Pattern is text-heavy, judgment-light, repeatable</td><td>Pattern requires deep domain judgment or live human interaction</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data availability</strong></td><td>We have 10+ examples of past good output to train against</td><td>We have no examples or only the user knows what good looks like</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Owner availability</strong></td><td>A named human will own this and use it weekly</td><td>Nobody specific cares; rollout would be top-down</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Low risk profile</strong></td><td>Output is internal-facing or reviewable before it ships</td><td>Output goes directly to customers or regulators with no checkpoint</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Worked example</span><h2 class="h2">Scoring a real workflow</h2><h3 class="h3">Workflow: Drafting B2B sales proposals (12-person SaaS team)</h3><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Time leverage: 5/5</strong> — saves ~8 hrs/proposal &times; 10 proposals/month = 80 hrs/month across the team.</li><li><strong>AI fit: 5/5</strong> — text-heavy, follows a repeatable structure.</li><li><strong>Data availability: 5/5</strong> — 30+ past winning proposals on file.</li><li><strong>Owner availability: 5/5</strong> — VP Sales will own it; she writes 4 proposals a week.</li><li><strong>Low risk: 4/5</strong> — output goes to prospects, but always reviewed by AE + senior leader.</li><li><strong>Total: 24/25.</strong> Top priority. This is what we shipped in week 4 of the rollout.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Workflow: AI-generated outbound sales emails at scale</h3><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Time leverage: 3/5</strong> — SDR team is small; impact moderate.</li><li><strong>AI fit: 3/5</strong> — model can write competent emails, but voice and personalization need work.</li><li><strong>Data availability: 2/5</strong> — only ~5 past outbound emails that converted, not enough to anchor voice.</li><li><strong>Owner availability: 4/5</strong> — SDR manager would own it.</li><li><strong>Low risk: 2/5</strong> — direct-to-prospect, low review threshold = brand risk.</li><li><strong>Total: 14/25.</strong> Backlog. Worth doing later after voice library is built.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Common mistakes</span><h2 class="h2">Where prioritization goes wrong</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Scoring on coolness instead of leverage.</strong> Voice agents are cool. Most companies do not get 5/5 on Time Leverage from voice. Score on the math, not the demo.</li><li><strong>Ignoring Owner Availability.</strong> No matter how high the leverage, a workflow with no owner will not ship. Owner Availability is a multiplier — not just a tie-breaker.</li><li><strong>Skipping the Low Risk score.</strong> The fastest way to kill an AI rollout politically is a single embarrassing customer-facing mistake. Pick low-risk workflows first to build trust.</li><li><strong>Doing 7 workflows at once.</strong> The top 3 method is not a suggestion. With 7, owners get diluted and nothing ships.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The ranked backlog</span><h2 class="h2">Where everything else goes</h2><p class="body">Workflows scoring 17-19: <strong>second wave</strong>, days 60-90 of the rollout, after the top 3 are stable.</p><p class="body">Workflows scoring 13-16: <strong>third wave</strong>, quarter 2, often with adjusted scope (e.g., add a human-review step to raise the Low Risk score).</p><p class="body">Workflows scoring below 13: <strong>parked</strong>. Revisit when conditions change — owner appears, data becomes available, model capability shifts.</p></div></section>

